entry.title: [Privacy Sandbox] Support enrollment overrides in chrome://flags
entry.content:
3rd party developers will need to test how their sites behave with

Privacy Sandbox APIs. However, sites are only allowed to use the APIs if

they have been enrolled/have agreed to the Privacy Sandbox attestations.

In order to unblock the developers if their site hasn't been enrolled,

this CL will let them to set a list of origins in their Chromium

instance that can use APIs (such as FLEDGE and Shared Storage) without

needing to check for enrollment.



Note that this approach is temporary. The long-term goal is to integrate

this feature into an upcoming Privacy Sandbox devtools extension. Until

the details of the extension integration have been hashed out, we are

implementing this using a flag.

entry.title: Fix SurfaceAnimationManager rect calculation
entry.content:
When SurfaceAnimationManager changes a SharedElementDrawQuad into a

CompositorRenderPassDrawQuad it uses a different coordinate space for

the |rect| and |visible_rect|. Both those fields are supposed to be in

the layer coordinate space [1] which generally matches the render pass

coordinate space. Luckily most things ignore RenderPassDrawQuad::rect

and just use the render pass |output_rect|, so it doesn't cause

problems, but update |rect| to match |visible_rect| for correctness.



Also update |vis_tex_coord| which is just the size of the render pass as

set from cc at [2].



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:cc/layers/render_surface_impl.cc;l=516;drc=df72e6aa6098446488f5045693111c9d129f524f

entry.title: Hold an AtomicString in KURL to simplify things.
entry.content:
As an optimization, KURL::Init() stores the input string as the string

spec if the input string is already atomic and canonicalized. This is

more efficient than constructing an AtomicString from the result of URL

canonicalization, since AtomicString construction requires hashing the

entire string and checking if it is present in the atomic string table.



Previously, WTF::String was thread-hostile, but could, in certain

circumstances, be moved between threads, while WTF::AtomicString was

thread-hostile and thread-bound. As a result, KURL::Init() skipped this

optimization if the input string wasn't already atomic, since converting

a non-atomic StringImpl into an atomic one would force the StringImpl to

become thread-bound.



Since https://crbug.com/1083392 is fixed now, the thread-safety issues

no longer apply anymore. In addition, since all paths that initialized

string_ turned it into an AtomicString first, just store an AtomicString

directly instead to make the intent clearer.



Finally, this also changes AtomicString::FromUTF8() calls to just

construct an 8-bit string directly, since the result of URL

canonicalization is a string that contains only ASCII characters.

entry.title: [fuchsia] Touch keystone manifest.json after SDK downloads
entry.content:
Touch the $sdk_root/meta/manifest.json file after fetching a new

SDK version, to trigger SDK-dependent build steps to be re-run.



The manifest.json is used as a keystone, to ensure that incremental

builds are correctly updated when e.g. SDK-provided tools change,

rather than relying on input dependencies on SDK-provided files

themselves, since the SDK files' timestamps usually reflect when

the SDK was built, not when it was unpacked on the build system.

entry.title: Remove obsolete/broken functionality from manage.py.
entry.content:
manage.py supports a number of different functions that are no longer

necessary and/or no longer work: writing the json files into a fixed

format, determining which gtests are not swarmed and converting gtests

to be swarmed. All of these operations work directly on the json files,

but those are output by generate_buildbot_json.py, so they already have

a format enforced by the generator and they can't be modified directly

because the pyl files that they are generated from need to be updated

(and dimensions would need to be specified on a per-builder basis).

Checking what tests need to be swarmed could maybe be useful, but it

fails because it attempts to do a git operation on a non-existent

directory, so it's clearly not being used.



The only functionality still being used is the check mode, which checks

that the isolates referenced by builders are defined in

gn_isolate_map.pyl and that the isolates defined in gn_isolate_map.pyl

are referenced by builders. This functionality is being used in

PRESUBMIT.py.

entry.title: [viz] Don't run tests of CopyOutputNV12() on Android
entry.content:
Android doesn't use NV12 GMB and doesn't support the MultiPlane::kNV12

format. Additionally, the test variants that use one SharedImage per

plane cannot be made to pass with Vulkan, as they require cross-thread

access and there is no SharedImage factory on Android that supports

cross-thread access for the required formats

(WrappedSkImageBackingFactory and ExternalVkImageBackingFactory don't

support cross-thread access, while AHardwareBufferImageBackingFactory

doesn't support the plane formats).

> Flags UI: Remove jstemplate.

> its usage in chrome://flags, which also makes the page less

> wasteful while rendering content.

>

> The template rendering strategy attached all available experiments into

entry.title: Fix carets placed in non-editable elements due to collapsed whitespace
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/c/3257487 and https://crrev.com/c/3620254 previously

made it so a caret inside an editable element couldn't cross into a

contained non-editable element as a result of adjusting the visually

equivalent position, when using `kCannotCrossEditingBoundary`.

However, in some cases involving collapsed whitespace between the

editing boundary and the edge of the editable element, the caret could

still cross into the non-editable element.



When the `MostForwardCaretPosition` and `MostBackwardCaretPosition`

functions are called with `kCannotCrossEditingBoundary`, they are

supposed to prevent crossing the editing boundary: the returned

position must be either null or have the same editability as the input

position. This is achieved by checking whether the anchor node at each

iterated position has the same editability as the previous one.



However, when the input position is beforeAnchor or afterAnchor, the

editability of the position might not be the same as the editability

of its anchor node. This is not checked, and thus it allows smuggling

an editing boundary before the check starts.



This patch fixes this by setting `start_editable` to whether the

position's container node is editable, rather than its anchor node,

if we are preventing crossing editable boundaries and allowing

snapping to the edges of inline nodes. `last_node` is similarly set to

the position's container node to detect if the first iterated position

has changed editability.



This bug was also causing an endless loop in cases where the

non-editable element contains an

crossing over into the non-editable element and it tries to position

itself inside the SVG, but

cannot find any valid position.



Bug: 1456664, 1384470

entry.title: [ios] Use unique identifier to name WebSession storage
entry.content:
Change WebSessionStateCache to use GetUniqueIdentifier() to generate

the file name of the session storage on disk. The migration happens

when the file are loaded by renaming them if they are still using the

serialisation code). Additionally, as the new serialisation code

won't save the GetStableIdentifier, this change allow having the

unchanging file name even if the new serialisation code is disabled

by kill-switch.



Include code to migrate the file to the new naming scheme, and an unit

entry.title: [@scope] Avoid invalidation flags based on in_rightmost_compound
entry.content:
When matching selectors against certain pseudo-classes,

we set flags to indicate that elements depend on those

pseudo-classes. To distinguish between elements that depend on

a pseudo-class directly and elements that are *related* to such

a dependency, we use the in_rightmost_compound flag.



This does not work well with @scope and the StyleScopeFrame cache,

because we evaluate the selectors in the @scope prelude *once*,

when the scope activations are first calculated. At that time,

:scope will either be in the subject position

(in_rightmost_compound=true), *or* in the non-subject position

(in_rightmost_compound=false), and the invalidation flags will be

marked accordingly. If we're matching another scoped selector later

with :scope in the opposite position, we'll hit the cache,

and neglect to set the flags we need.



In preparation of solving this problem, this CL introduces

"impact" to SelectorCheckingContext, which controls directly how

flags should be set. The critical difference between this and

in_rightmost_compound is that it's possible to specify impact=kBoth,

which will cause *both* subject/non-subject flags to set. This will

be used by @scope in a future CL.
